Since this don&#39;t give any additional value to the `valueOf(String name)` method, it only makes sense to define an additional method if we want have a different behavior. If we don&#39;t want to raise an `IllegalArgumentException` we can change the implementation to:

      private enum Blah {
        A, B, C, D;
    
        public static Blah valueOfOrDefault(String name, Blah defaultValue) {
          switch (name) {
            case &quot;A&quot;:
              return A;
            case &quot;B&quot;:
              return B;
            case &quot;C&quot;:
              return C;
            case &quot;D&quot;:
              return D;
            default:
              if (defaultValue == null) {
                throw new NullPointerException();
              }
              return defaultValue;
          }
        }
      }

By providing a default value we keep the [contract][1] of `Enum.valueOf(String name)` without throwing an `IllegalArgumentException`  in that manner that in no case `null` is returned. Therefore we throw a `NullPointerException` if the name is `null` and in case of `default` if `defaultValue` is `null`. That&#39;s how `valueOfOrDefault` works.

This approach adopts the design of the `Map`-Interface which provides a method `Map.getOrDefault(Object key, V defaultValue)` as of Java 8.


